RT @PharmaFactz: Facts about Rituximab

Rituximab treat autoimmune disorders & various kinds of cancer; leukemias & lymphomas. 

Complications:

- Infusion reaction
- Cardiac arrest
- Tumor lysis syndrome
- Risk of infections
- Bowel obstruction

Binds to CD20 protein; widely expressed on B cells

RT @PharmaFactz: Selective Estrogen Receptor Modulators (SERMs)

Eg. clomifene, raloxifene, toremifene

- Clomifene treats infertility in women who do not ovulate.

- Raloxifene is used to treat osteoporosis and reduce risk of invasive breast cancer.

- Toremifene treats advanced breast cancer.

RT @PharmaFactz: Ondansetron is used to prevent nausea and vomiting caused by:

•Cancer chemotherapy
•Radiation therapy
•Surgery

It works as a 5-HT3 antagonist.

Side effects include diarrhea, constipation, headache, sleepiness and itchiness. It is also known to prolong the QT interval.

conditions. #mycancerview

Risk factors: 
Like most cancers, older age is the strongest
risk factor for breast cancer. Many other factors that
influence risk modify exposure of breast tissue to
reproductive hormones. #mycancerview

Some of these are potentially
modifiable, such as weight gain after the age of 18 and/or
being overweight or obese (for postmenopausal breast
cancer), postmenopausal hormone use (combined
estrogen and progestin), physical inactivity, and alcohol
consumption #mycancerview

Factors related to medical history that
increase risk include a personal or family history of
breast or ovarian cancer; inherited mutations (genetic
alterations) in BRCA1, BRCA2, or other breast cancer
susceptibility genes; #mycancerview

; a history of ductal or
lobular carcinoma in situ; high-dose radiation to the
chest at a young age (e.g., for treatment of lymphoma);
high breast tissue density (the amount of glandular tissue
relative to fatty tissue measured on a mammogram); and obesity #mycancerview.

RT @DrOlufunmilayo: Another symptom of testicular cancer is the scrotum feels heavier and fuller.

So don’t panic. Just see a doctor.

RT @DrOlufunmilayo: So what is Testicular Cancer?

Testicular cancer is an illness in which malignant (cancer) cells form in the tissues of one or both testicles.
That’s the simplest way to define it.

RT @DrOlufunmilayo: In #TesticularCancer, usually the lump/swelling is painless. Most of the time, a painful testis points to an infection or trauma. However in very few men with the cancer, they may report pain.
But this is not classical for testicular cancer.

13/

RT @DrOlufunmilayo: Another symptom of testicular cancer is the scrotum feels heavier and fuller. 

However this may also happen in a condition called hydrocele which is not a cancer- but your doctor can easily differentiate the two by a bedside light test.

So don’t panic. Just see a doctor.

RT @DrOlufunmilayo: How is #TesticularCancer diagnosed?

Usually it’s a combination of examination of the testicles by a doctor, some blood tests, scans and an eventual surgery to take out the testis IF the tests and scans suggests it is cancer.

That’s the simplest way to define it.
It’s basically cancer of/in the testicles due to abnormal growth in it.

RT @DrOlufunmilayo: How common is #TesticularCancer?

I don’t have figures for Nigeria sadly,
but in UK around 2,200 men are diagnosed with testicular cancer a year. 

That's about 1 out of every 100 cancers (1%) diagnosed in men. And it’s regarded as the commonest Cancer in men 20-35years old.

RT @DrOlufunmilayo: Other risk factors for #TesticularCancer are 

-Having fertility problems as a man (like having a low sperm concentration or 
sperm that seems to move slowly or having a high proportion of abnormal sperm)

-having had testicular cancer in the past

-being a white man

11/

RT @DrOlufunmilayo: -Having an abnormality in the penis and its opening (hypospadias)
-Having a groin hernia
-Having HIV/AIDS 
-Being quite taller than average

These are all recognised “risks” but it doesn’t 100% mean the person will surely have testicular cancer. 
Only says the risk is there.

RT @DrOlufunmilayo: In #TesticularCancer, usually the lump/swelling is painless. Most of the time, a painful testis points to an infection or trauma. However in very few men with the cancer, they may report pain.
But this is not classical for testicular cancer.

RT @DrOlufunmilayo: Another symptom of testicular cancer is the scrotum feels heavier and fuller. 

However this may also happen in a condition called hydrocele which is not a cancer- but your doctor can easily differentiate the two by a bedside light test.

So don’t panic. Just see a doctor.

14/

RT @DrOlufunmilayo: How is #TesticularCancer diagnosed?

Usually it’s a combination of examination of the testicles by a doctor, some blood tests, scans and an eventual surgery to take out the testis IF the tests and scans suggests it is cancer.

15/

RT @DrOlufunmilayo: What is the survival rate of #TesticularCancer ?

The good news here is that for men who have stage 1 cancer of the testis (testis has not spread beyond the testis), more than 95 out of 100 men will be alive and well 5 years or more after the diagnosis.
That’s the good news.

16/

RT @DrOlufunmilayo: However remember I said the good news is IF the cancer is detected when it is still confined totally to the testis.
That survival rate begins to drop IF the cancer is detected late or it has spread beyond the testis.
Then it becomes a real serious problem.

RT @DrOlufunmilayo: What’s the Treatment Options for testicular cancer?

Usually the treatment depends on the stage of the cancer (how far it has gone); but generally the treatment is to surgically remove the testis plus/minus chemotherapy and radiotherapy.
And follow up as well.
